 Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic ...", "content": "Would anyone who knows about how can we calculate WER for ASR.. please give me an example so I can calculate WER for ASR in multiple sentences that I have in my app\n\nYou can use this Python package:\n\nif you need other languages, let us know which ones.\n\nNikolay Shmyrev's user avatar\n\n## 1 Comment\n\nAdd a comment\n\na simple C++ implementation Based on Levenshtein distance,\njust a single file without any library.\n\nAlok Prasad's user avatar\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nRefer to this repository to calculate the Word Error Rate (WER) of two strings with Colab.\n\nYou can also remove the punctuation when calculate WER by tick on the remote\\_punctuation checkbox.\n\nenter image description here\n\nenter image description here\n\nWord Error Rate Visualization with Colab: \n\nKenny's user avatar\n\n## Comments [...] To answer your specific questions:\n\n1. Punctuation & Capitalization:\nStrip punctuation and convert to lowercase before calculation.\n\n`from jiwer import wer\nimport string\ndef clean_text(text):\n# Remove punctuation and lowercase\ntext = text.lower()\ntext = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))\nreturn text\nreference = \"The cat, sat on the mat.\"\nhypothesis = \"The cat sit on the mat\"\nwer_score = wer(clean_text(reference), clean_text(hypothesis))`\n\n2. Substitutions, Insertions, Deletions:\nEach error type has equal weight in the standard WER formula.\n\n3. Manual Example:\n\n`Reference: \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nHypothesis: \"the cat sit on mat\"\nErrors:\n- \"sat\" → \"sit\" = 1 Substitution\n- \"the\" deleted = 1 Deletion\nWER = (1 + 0 + 1) / 6 = 0.333 = 33.3%` [...] Now the question arises how to identify these types of errors, for identifying these errors. For this Levenshtein distance metric is used.\n\nThe Levenshtein distance is a measurement of the differences between two “strings.” The strings are sequences of letters that make up the words in a transcription.\n\nLet’s look at some examples for better understanding\n\nAfter this get the total number of words and get the division done, this will give you WER\n\nNaval's user avatar\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nQuick Answer: Use the `jiwer` library for Python - it handles all the complexity for you:\n\n`jiwer`\n`from jiwer import wer\nreference = \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nhypothesis = \"the cat sit on the mat\"\nerror_rate = wer(reference, hypothesis)\nprint(f\"WER: {error_rate:.2%}\") # Output: WER: 16.67%`", "score": 0.4184836, "raw_content": "### [current community](https://stackoverflow.com)\n\n### your communities\n\n### [more stack exchange communities](https://stackexchange.com/sites)\n\nCommunities for your favorite technologies. [Explore all Collectives](/collectives-all)\n\nStack Overflow for Teams is now called **Stack Internal**. Bring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n\nBring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n[Learn more](https://stackoverflow.co/internal/?utm_medium=referral&utm_source=stackoverflow-community&utm_campaign=side-bar&utm_content=explore-teams-compact)\n\n##### Collectives™ on Stack Overflow\n\nFind centralized, trusted content and collaborate around the technologies you use most.\n\n**Stack Internal**\n\nKnowledge at work\n\nBring the best of human thought and AI automation together at your work.\n\n# [How Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic Speech Recognition)?](/questions/59126899/how-can-i-evaluate-wer-word-error-rate-in-asr-automatic-speech-recognition)\n\nHow Can I evaluate WER (Word Error Rate) in ASR ( Automatic Speech Recognition)?\n\nFor Example, If I have (Human Ref. Translation) for the sentences and Output of ASR.\n\nI know the equation but I do not know how to calculate it. Do I enter punctuation marks such as a comma and full stop and so on in the calculation of WER?\n\nAs well as for sub, ins, and del of words. Is there a specific weight? Each of them when calculated in the equation?\n\nWould anyone who knows about how can we calculate WER for ASR.. please give me an example so I can calculate WER for ASR in multiple sentences that I have in my app\n\n![Randa Taiseer's user avatar](https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-1PWGnqrJ0T4/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/ACHi3rdTWIdwBTPddRrn9KumTWkLF6Im4w/s64-rj/photo.jpg)\n\n## 5 Answers 5\n\nDo I enter punctuation marks such as a comma and full stop and so on in the calculation of WER?\n\nYou strip punctuation before calculation and convert everything to lowercase.\n\nWould anyone who knows about how can we calculate WER for ASR.. please give me an example so I can calculate WER for ASR in multiple sentences that I have in my app\n\nYou can use this Python package:\n\n<https://pypi.org/project/jiwer/>\n\nif you need other languages, let us know which ones.\n\n![Nikolay Shmyrev's user avatar](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6c16a68dfa5030f9b6df4d4ae4a337a?s=64&d=identicon&r=PG)\n\n## 1 Comment\n\nAdd a comment\n\n![](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4713003a4a6967ae5048d2c9062fc6bf?s=48&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2)\n\na simple C++ implementation Based on Levenshtein distance,\njust a single file without any library.\n\n<https://github.com/alokprasad/asr-wer>\n\n![Alok Prasad's user avatar](https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-z9fJSHYTzU4/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAG7k/4kr-m1Is0TY/s64-rj/photo.jpg)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nRefer to this [repository](https://github.com/duckyngo/Word-Error-Rate-Visualization-with-Colab) to calculate the Word Error Rate (WER) of two strings with Colab.\n\nYou can also remove the punctuation when calculate WER by tick on the remote\\_punctuation checkbox.\n\n[![enter image description here](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)\n\n![enter image description here](https://i.sstatic.net/oNRLQ.png)\n\nWord Error Rate Visualization with Colab: <https://github.com/duckyngo/Word-Error-Rate-Visualization-with-Colab>\n\n![Kenny's user avatar](https://i.sstatic.net/Mi9L0.jpg?s=64)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\nWord Error Rate is calculated based on formula:\n\n**Word Error Rate = (Substitutions + Insertions + Deletions) / Number of Words Spoken**\n\nIf we analyze this is very simple, we have first get the total number of Insertions, Deletions and substitutions in the ASR output by comparing with the actual transcript data (ground truth data). Now Insertion can happen at character level or word level or can be a combination of many characters, similarly deletion can also happen at multiple characters level, similarly in place of characters or words, new characters can also be wrongly inferenced which is basically substitution error.\n\nNow the question arises how to identify these types of errors, for identifying these errors. For this **Levenshtein distance** metric is used.\n\nThe Levenshtein distance is a measurement of the differences between two “strings.” The strings are sequences of letters that make up the words in a transcription.\n\nLet’s look at some examples for better understanding\n\nAfter this get the total number of words and get the division done, this will give you WER\n\n![Naval's user avatar](https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e1f2e5223ae784673b11533900fae53c?s=64&d=identicon&r=PG)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\n**Quick Answer:** Use the `jiwer` library for Python - it handles all the complexity for you:\n\n`jiwer`\n`from jiwer import wer\nreference = \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nhypothesis = \"the cat sit on the mat\"\nerror_rate = wer(reference, hypothesis)\nprint(f\"WER: {error_rate:.2%}\") # Output: WER: 16.67%`\n\n**To answer your specific questions:**\n\n**1. Punctuation & Capitalization:**\nStrip punctuation and convert to lowercase **before** calculation.\n\n`from jiwer import wer\nimport string\ndef clean_text(text):\n# Remove punctuation and lowercase\ntext = text.lower()\ntext = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))\nreturn text\nreference = \"The cat, sat on the mat.\"\nhypothesis = \"The cat sit on the mat\"\nwer_score = wer(clean_text(reference), clean_text(hypothesis))`\n\n**2. Substitutions, Insertions, Deletions:**\nEach error type has **equal weight** in the standard WER formula.\n\n**3. Manual Example:**\n\n`Reference: \"the cat sat on the mat\"\nHypothesis: \"the cat sit on mat\"\nErrors:\n- \"sat\" → \"sit\" = 1 Substitution\n- \"the\" deleted = 1 Deletion\nWER = (1 + 0 + 1) / 6 = 0.333 = 33.3%`\n\nWhen I manually annotated transcriptions, I found it helpful to use a spreadsheet with columns for S, I, and D counts per sentence.\n\n![Erck's user avatar](https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJxk5wLQxUOTLesiDCUVgwzSMEE2n-a-tGH33lDrvA=k-s64)\n\n## Comments\n\nAdd a comment\n\n## Your Answer\n\nThanks for contributing an answer to Stack Overflow!\n\nBut *avoid* …\n\nTo learn more, see our [tips on writing great answers](/help/how-to-answer).\n\n### Sign up or [log in](/users/login?ssrc=question_page&returnurl=https%3a%2f%2fstackoverflow.com%2fquestions%2f59126899%2fhow-can-i-evaluate-wer-word-error-rate-in-asr-automatic-speech-recognition%23new-answer)\n\n### Post as a guest\n\nRequired, but never shown\n\n### Post as a guest\n\nRequired, but never shown\n\nBy clicking “Post Your Answer”, you agree to our [terms of service](https://stackoverflow.com/legal/terms-of-service/public) and acknowledge you have read our [privacy policy](https://stackoverflow.com/legal/privacy-policy).\n\nStart asking to get answers\n\nFind the answer to your question by asking.\n\nExplore related questions\n\nSee similar questions with these tags.\n\n### Related\n\n#### [Hot Network Questions](https://stackexchange.com/questions?tab=hot)\n\n# Subscribe to RSS\n\nTo subscribe to this RSS feed, copy and paste this URL into your RSS reader.\n\n![](/posts/59126899/ivc/94b9?prg=e99351bc-27b4-4089-9ad7-dd76a2498546)\n\n##### [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com)\